e following a recipe step-by-step. For example, if you know the first term =
is 2 and each term is double the one before it, you can write a formula tha=
t says =E2=80=9Cto get the next term, multiply the current term by 2.=E2=80=
=9D This is useful when the sequence builds on itself in a clear way.<br><b=
r>On the other hand, an explicit formula gives you a direct way to find any=
 term in the sequence without having to know the previous ones. It=E2=80=99=
s like having a shortcut. For the same sequence where each term is double t=
he previous one, the explicit formula would be =E2=80=9Cthe ( n )-th term i=
s ( 2^n ).=E2=80=9D This means you can find the 10th term just by plugging =
in 10 for ( n ), without calculating all the terms before it.<br><br>So, yo=
u use a recursive formula when it=E2=80=99s easier to see how each term rel=
ates to the one before it, and an explicit formula when you want a quick wa=
y to find any term directly. With practice, you=E2=80=99ll get a feel for w=
hich one to use based on the problem you=E2=80=99re solving. Does that make=
